<head><title>The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui</title></head>
<body>
	<div class="entry-meta"><a class="entry-date published">December 1, 2017</a></div>

<p>Brecht left Berlin in 1933 the morning after the Reichstag fire, which is loosely depicted in our play. Hitler had been Chancellor for less than two months, and Brecht was part of an exodus of communist, Jewish, queer and otherwise subversive artists who had thrived in the Weimar Republic at the same time the Nazi Party gained influence.</p>
<p>He wrote <i>The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui</i> in three weeks in 1941, just before he came to the United States. A version of Ui first appeared in a short story he started and abandoned in 1934 called "Life and Deeds of Giacomo Ui of Padua," which similarly created a scale model of Hitler's rise, set instead in Italy on a backdrop of machine politics. He later transplanted Ui to Chicago.</p>
<p>Like many Weimar artists, Brecht was enamored with America, specifically the world of Chicago gangsters he had might have seen in films like Warner Brothers' <i>Little Caesar</i> with Edward G. Robinson and <i>The Public Enemy</i> with James Cagney. <i>Arturo Ui</o> almost follows the trajectory of these films: the meteoric rise of a gangster and his subsequent fall. But Hitler's fall was nowhere in sight at the time Brecht wrote. The play's last event, the annexation of Cicero, corresponds to the 1938 annexation of Austria, three years before Brecht's writing in 1941.</p>
<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*7bRmwQpzZQsPAu8uKrnYMg@2x.jpeg" width="100%">
<p>Brecht was not the first one to recognize gangsterism in the Nazis' seizure of power, and he certainly wasn't the last. We recognize Hitler and other leaders like him in Arturo Ui, but what we see onstage is a pathetic, insecure opportunist.</p>
<p>As a theorist, one of Brecht's most influential ideas is <i>Verfremdungseffekt</i> - the effect of "making strange" or "estrangement effect," also called alienation or distance, which calls attention to the artifice of performance. It's also described as making the familiar unfamiliar. With <i>Arturo Ui</i>, Brecht has taken the familiar figure of Hitler and made him strange by placing him into a gangster story. What's more, this is world spoken in verse - simultaneously elevating a lowly gangster while tearing men of power down from their pedestals.</i>
<i>Our Hitler figure is made all the more strange in Glynnis Kunkel-Ruiz. In <i>Mein Kampf</i>, Hitler wrote: "The people in their overwhelming majority are so feminine by nature and attitude that sober reasoning determines their thoughts and actions far less than emotion and feeling." With a cast of mostly women, it's worth keeping in mind the hypermasculinity of Nazism.</p>
<p><i>Arturo Ui</i> does not address many Nazi atrocities that most American audiences are familiar with. "Ui is a parable play," Brecht wrote. "The circle described has been deliberately restricted; it is confined to the plane of state, industrialists, Junkers and petty bourgeois…. The play does not pretend to give a complete account of the historical situation in the 1930s." This itself is a form of alienation; we are not distracted by what we know about Nazism, but allowed to see how it happened.</i>
<i>There's been a temptation which other theaters have indulged to create an Arturo Ui that reflects a current world leader, but our belief is that the play as it is demystifies totalitarianism with Hitler as an example, not the rule. Brecht says as much in the epilogue, added after the war: "That was the thing that had us mastered / So let's not drop our guard too quickly then. / Although the world stood up to the bastard / The bitch that bore him is in heat again."</p>
